After a tree is removed due to storm damage or urban development Arbor Upcycle will strive to salvage the tree for its timber. The tree is then milled into slabs on-site or at our warehouse. fast.name: 2004 Mazda 6 Sport - Fast & Reliable
fast.description: Unfortunately it is time to pass on my absolutely amazing 2004 Mazda 6 Sport Hatchback! It is in great condition, serviced frequently and well taken care of by our local and trusted mechanic at Advanced Auto in Santa Cruz. Runs perfectly, drove it to Yosemite last week and Anaheim about a month ago with absolutely no problems. Great gas mileage and a comfortable ride for road trips. Always received premium gas and oil changes every 3,000 miles.Completely upgraded the sound system with a 12inch kicker subwoofer and new speakers and amp (Sounds Incredible). I also put in a touchscreen Pioneer center display that is bluetooth capable and has a usb hookup for your phone to charge and play music. I also installed a back-up camera! This car has really been well taken care of and I am sad to see it go but I am in need of something a bit bigger. There are some signs of age as you can see in the seats and body and the text in the center screen is starting to fade a bit (See Photos). But these minor cosmetic blemishes are truly only aesthetic and do not take away from how amazing this car drives. There are no mechanical issues at all, sometimes a bit of oil does burn off the engine resulting in a smell but we have confirmed with our mechanic that there is no underlying issue associated with this. It’s fast and reliable and will get you where you need to go in comfort and style.The price is $5250 Obo and please feel free to reach out with ANY questions or to schedule a test drive!

famous.name: Fender Twin II, JBL version, 1982, hand wired!
famous.description: => Offering the slightly rare, but still great, Fender Rivera Twin - with factory JBLs! These ‘E120’s  are a continuation of the legendary ‘D120’s (that were premium options on earlier Fender amps!)! So the ‘voice’ of this one is going to be different from a ‘bone stock Twin Reverb II’… Aside from a bit of cosmetic wear - it is just serviced -and sounds amazing.=> There seems to be a lot of misinformation about this model... What you should know is that ‘channel one’ contains the entire original ‘black face era’ Fender circuit… While Rivera did make some changes to resistors and capacitors to allow a gain channel to share the preamp - his ‘clean’ channel still has that immediately familiar Fender vibe… Rivera’s design revisions included a new universal ‘acoustic presence’ control (not on previous Twins) to effectively offset the slightly ‘darker’ voicing... And please note - your Reverb is now also exists in channel one! So think of this as your old ‘channel two’ (minus ‘tremolo’ - which you can run through the new effects loop!). The JBLs are game changers:Any combo with these speakers is going to be its own animal tonally - and unlike others of its kind. They put out so much sound across all frequencies that your ‘power curve’ will be unique to ‘this model plus the JBLs’! That said - it is a little less bright (or scooped) than other Twins - if you just set your EQ ‘flat’ - with the Presence control and ‘Brightness’ off! But Rivera’s design did add the new ‘acoustic presence’ feature (as noted), as an offset - to dial in more upper frequencies - and of course - you’re going to set the tri-band EQ to your liking! So scoop away! Ultimately you can shape your guitar tone to be very close to a legacy Twin’s… The ‘E120’s will deliver upper range clarity like you’ve never heard, anyway... The ‘brightness’ can easily be worked out with the various controls provided and your guitar settings. But you cannot rig the floor shaking power and definition of these JBLs with the regular speakers (which aren’t bad either, IMHO).Famous JBL E120 users:Turns out both Garcia and SRV liked these in their stage rigs. Please note that both of these guys liked a bright, clear base tone, to start off with - and any effects got layered on from there. Obviously Jerry was known for his very long form leads - often coming into a mix with five other instruments vamping or soloing away behind him… I was not in the SRV club when he played New Years Eve at Henry Kaiser. Can say that he played some of the longest, cleanest, and most fluid lead lines - with notes that seemed to just fly through the air (and no, I wasn’t on anything at the time!). Apparently the ‘E’ speaker may have been the brightest of the ‘120’ series, and featured a ceramic magnet… So this would seem to offset any concerns about the Rivera Twin being ‘too dark’. New features and improvements on this amp:  The reverb now works in both channels! Finally! So your clean tone palette is now in channel one, and, Fyi - it still has more in common with a ‘blackface’ or ‘silverface’ Twin than not! Rumors of the differences have been greatly exaggerated (to say the least!). As mentioned - the new ‘acoustic presence’ control is in both channels - and does add a tapered high to upper mid range ‘bump’ (on your frequency curve). The Fender ‘JBL option’ was a ‘deluxe’ release - adding speakers that will make you rethink what you thought you knew about great sound! Believe me - I have considered doing a ‘head-cab’ conversion just to keep them.Paul Rivera’s early eighties amps were the last of the hand wired Fenders. Sound-wise - they offer a bridge from the past to the present... Many users have said that ‘channel one’ sounds very much like a legacy Twin (of the nineteen sixties) - while the gain channel points in some new directions... Yes, exactly! As mentioned - the ‘clean’ side of this combo can be adjusted to sound very much like an ‘original Twin’ - and now there is ‘universal’ reverb… Fyi - the amp can be fully ‘black faced’ by a competent tech (with about a half dozen changes to some resistors and capacitors)… It is fully hackable, for those with real electronics skills… But you shouldn’t need to! The great quality is already there. No modifications needed (but you can, if it matters).With a dedicated lead/ drive circuit - you can now ‘preset’ this Twin with extra midrange and ‘edge’ for your solos or lead breaks... You just need to master the second channel… The ‘drive’ effect requires a bit more study to dial in than on some ‘high gain’ amps, but it is most definitely there! And it can be had at reasonable volumes. You just need to learn how it works… Of course, if you are interested in buying the amp, I would be happy to share these ‘secrets’. None of the internet ‘buzz’ about this model makes the ‘Twin II’ a lessor amp... ‘Your sound’ is still very much ‘in the box’. You just dial it in a little differently... The ‘JBL Twins’:The James B Lansing speakers are now really sought after... There’s a silverface ‘JBL’ Twin for sale nearby for a mere $1899.00 ! It features the earlier ‘D120’ versions of what’s in this amp… So there you go… $845 versus $1899... A friend of mine does play through a ‘blackface’ Twin - and my first lead player’s amp was an early silverface. This one is not so different - given these special speakers. As mentioned, the Fender labeled ‘E120s’ are just early eighties updates of the ‘D’ series JBLs offered in the sixties and seventies.  There’s a promo for them in the gallery above. Fender applied their own ‘in-house’ stock numbers and labeling, which can be translated, if you’re curious. But tone freaks take note - they are a very different animal than the ‘stock’ Fender blue labels (which are good speakers IMHO) - or even most competitors… Any solos or power chords played through these ‘E120’s will cut through like nothing else. You’ll be ‘driving that train’ - not sitting in the caboose.The 18 pound magnets can take a 300 watt ‘dynamic peak’ - while the amp is only pushing 105 watts (continuous). Cannot emphasize how great they sound! Purchased separately - the ‘120’s can be had for a mere four hundred dollars a pair (or one for two fifty)... ‘Lansing’ were an industry leader from the 1940’s on; a deep tech powerhouse. Ask any sound engineer.Why does this amp offer the best of ‘then and now’?As noted, the ‘cleans’ are less scooped than a ‘blackface’ or ‘silverface’ version - it’s true (eg. less ‘bright’). But they are just as rich and detailed - offering good top end ‘chime’ and enough decibels to reach the back row of almost any club! The newly added ‘Presence’ knob is your voicing ‘offset’. It will work better than the legacy ‘Brightness’ adjustment - if you’re looking for more ‘Fender sparkle’! That is still ‘in the box’… But now you get the advantages of a true ‘lead-drive’ preset - that can be used as a ‘clean’ midrange or ‘edge-boost’ - leave alone that you can do full on ‘crunch’ and ‘grind’! Can’t exactly do all of that with your ‘legacy’ Twin!  The Rivera Fenders have suffered needlessly from too many comparisons to Randall Smith’s amps. It’s an almost pointless comparison IMHO. Both are great designs with their unique advantages. But you won’t get ‘cleans’ like this one can do on those, IMHO.As noted - the Rivera ‘gain channels’ can all be ‘overdriven’ at modest volumes - given you know how to do the settings... This runs contrary to some online chatter. Would be happy to share the exact tweaks needed, if you’re curious... The settings are less obvious than on some amps - but once you know, you know! Of course, you can also plug in your favorite tube screamer. Unfortunately, I do not have the original two button Fender ‘footswitch’ channel controller (although they are available on almost any swap board).Condition:It has been well cared for overall: obviously gigged in the past - but fully retubed by a fairly recent owner… There is a matched quad of reissue ‘Sovtek 5881/6L6WGC’s - sounding very warm and punchy. Also a septet of mostly newer ‘Ruby’ preamp tubes... If you’re not familiar, these are hand chosen brands from a ‘current market’ selection... Ruby applies their own ‘in house’ testing - after which acceptable valves are ‘rebranded’ - leaving the original maker’s mark on the glass underneath... A ‘Ruby/ Jan Phillips 12AT7’ can be seen in the PI spot (above) - while a row of mostly ‘Ruby/ Tesla’ built 12AX7s (mis-marked as ‘E83CC/12ax7’) occupy V1 - V6...The amp has just been electronically cleaned; valves re-tensioned; and all thoroughly tested by Phil Milner Amps and Electronics Repair, of San Rafael (per the invoice shown). There is a new speaker wire harness to run the JBLs. All is in order - and the amp is ready for your studio or a live performance. The bottom line:A ‘fresh approach’ will yield dividends: clean, gritty,‘driven’, or boosted… Your call... The Twin II does drive 105 watts as needed... For jazz and funk fans (like yours truly) - the ‘normal’ channel has plenty of warmth and ‘spank’ - while ‘channel two’ can be set up for solos. Metal may require an extra pedal - but blues-rock, and classic crunch, are all dial-able as is. When it comes to live sound and voicing - your speakers are a game changer... Comparisons to amps of the past may serve to explain differences - but sometimes they get in the way of ‘the here and now’.Message me with your questions.Can deliver in the Greater Bay Area.Thanks for checking out the ad!  - David

famous.name: Ashdown Rootmaster 420W Solid State 2x12 Bass Combo,w/ Sub Harmonics
famous.description: Only ever been played a few times,(inside/practice only, never used for a live gig which was the original intention, so it is basically unused). I am not mobile with a car, so only reach out if you are willing to drive over/commute to Hayes Valley and pick it up, serious inquiries only please. Rootmaster heads, combos and cabinets draw on all of our experience working with some of the biggest bands in the world to deliver workhorse reliability, creative tone-shaping, comprehensive recording and performing facilities plus the sonic slam you need to underpin your band's performances night after night - all at a price that won't break the bank.Powered by 420W digital amp, it is ideal for players who favors a tight, defined sound, delivering it's power via a pair of 12 custom, supplemented by a high-frequency piezo for increased top end bite and articulation.Simple, powerful EQIt all starts with an ultra-low-noise instrument input where the accompanying Input Level control helps you perfectly match the output of your bass. Five-band rotary tone controls act with surgical precision to provide total control over your sound, while a Shape switch instantly dials you in to a classic Ashdown tone setting, straight from the world-famous ABM.One-knob CompressionInstantly adding warmth and body to your tone, this simple to use, great sounding compressor delivers a powerful, even sound to make sure your bass will fill out any mix.Footswitchable variable overdriveWith footswitchable flexibility, our tube-emulated overdrive can take your core bass sound and push it into warm overdrive through to distorted filth whenever you need to add extra grind and girth to your tone.Kick it downBringing extra depth and definition to your bass parts, the Sub-Harmonic Generator lets you dial in a sub-octave and kick it in via footswitch whenever you need the extra depth for those super-heavy Godzilla moments.Totally connectedIf you want to use your favorite pedals or multi-effects, you'll find send and return sockets on the back panel, along with a DI output for direct injection into the PA mixer or recording console and a Line Input (with front panel level control) so you can jam along with a backing track in rehearsal.Create the perfect rig2 x 10, 4 x 10 and 2 x 12 cabs all feature custom-designed Ashdown bass drivers plus a high-frequency horn for additional top-end bite. A 1 x 15 completes the range with all cabinets featuring ultra-cool retro cloth grilles, road-ready tolex covering and tough metal protective corners.
